{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"60aafea6-98a3-4dad-a1a2-a85479337921","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in a minimal image, copy the tool from a sidecar or use `kubectl cp` to bring in `dotnet-trace`.\n- For a Speedscope-compatible format, add `--format speedscope`.\n- If you need OS-level detail (native frames, kernel), use **`dotnet-counters`** first to confirm managed CPU is high, then consider `perf` or `dotnet-trace` with `--clreventlevel verbose`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0fb7c1a4-b7c1-4d12-ba9d-8c91cd0fe51a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":312},"id":"003b2da0-b7cb-4f2a-b4eb-f88b85c2cab4","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:49:12.271Z","parentId":"f15cd6fd-18db-4246-9990-b2843ad29e2e"}
